SENATE AND ASSEMBLY, DO ENACT AS FOLLOWS:
1 Section 1. NRS 388.395 is hereby amended to read as follows:
2 388.395 1. The board of trustees of a school district or the governing body
3 of a charter school may apply to the State Board of Education for a grant for a
4 program of career and technical education, to be paid for from the remainder of
5 state money described in subsection 3 of NRS 388.392.
6 2. The State Board of Education shall review all applications submitted
7 pursuant to subsection 1 and award grants based on the criteria established by
8 regulation of the State Board of Education.
9 3. The proportion of the total amount awarded pursuant to subsection 2 to a
10 school district or charter school during a fiscal year must not exceed the proportion
11 of the enrollment of pupils in advanced courses within programs of career and
12 technical education in the school district or charter school during the previous fiscal
13 year, as compared to the enrollments of pupils in advanced courses within
14 programs of career and technical education throughout the State during the previous
15 fiscal year.
16 4. As used in this section:
17 (a) “Advanced course” means:
18 (1) A CTE concentrator course;
19 (2) A work-based learning program pursuant to NRS 389.167;
20 (3) An activity for pupils to earn industry-recognized credentials, as
21 identified by the Governor’s Office of Workforce Innovation pursuant to
22 paragraph (d) of subsection 4 of NRS 232.975;
23 (4) A dual credit course in a program of career and technical education;
24 or
25 (5) A course in a program of career and technical education that
26 requires the completion of a CTE concentrator course as a prerequisite for
27 enrollment.
28 (b) “CTE concentrator” has the meaning ascribed to it in 20 U.S.C. §
29 2302(12).
30 (c) “CTE concentrator course” means a course within a program of career
31 and technical education which may be used, in combination with another course,
32 to meet the course requirements to be a CTE concentrator.
33 Sec. 2. NRS 389.167 is hereby amended to read as follows:
34 389.167 1. A pupil enrolled at a public school must be allowed to apply one
35 or more credits toward the total number of credits required for graduation from high
36 school if the pupil successfully completes the number of hours in a work-based
37 learning program required by regulation of the State Board to earn such credits.
38 Any credits earned for successful completion of a work-based learning program
39 must be applied toward the pupil’s elective course credits and not toward a course
40 that is required for graduation from high school.
41 2. The board of trustees of a school district or the governing body of a charter
42 school may offer a work-based learning program upon application to and with the
43 approval of the Superintendent of Public Instruction. An application to offer a
44 work-based learning program must include, without limitation:

